     1	# Perf gates — the two-tier model
     2	
     3	FathomDB has **two** perf-gate tiers that exercise the *same* production read
     4	path (`Engine::search` → FTS5 MATCH + two-phase bit-KNN + f32 rerank) at
     5	different scales, with different jobs:
     6	
     7	| Tier | File | Runs | N | Job |
     8	|---|---|---|---|---|
     9	| **Devloop** | `crates/fathomdb-engine/tests/perf_gates_devloop.rs` | always, in `cargo test` | ≈1000 | fast inner-loop signal (seconds) |
    10	| **Canonical** | `crates/fathomdb-engine/tests/perf_gates.rs` | `AGENT_LONG=1` only | 10k binding / 100k / 1M | ship verdict |
    11	
    12	The devloop tier is the subject of 0.7.2 PR-6. The canonical tier is the
    13	ADR-locked release verdict (PR-3); this doc explains how the two relate so a
    14	green devloop run is never mistaken for a ship verdict (or vice versa).
    15	
    16	---
    17	
    18	## Why two tiers
    19	
    20	The canonical gates are slow: the real-embedder N=1M measurement is infeasible
    21	on CI (~166 h of serialized BGE seed; see
    22	`dev/plans/runs/0.7.2-PR-3-output.json`), so they are `AGENT_LONG`-gated and run
    23	as a once-per-release local exercise. That leaves the inner dev loop with **no
    24	perf signal at all** between releases — a latency or vector-wiring regression
    25	could land and sit unnoticed until the next canonical run.
    26	
    27	The devloop tier fills that gap: a ≈1000-doc subset (via PR-5's `CorpusFixture`)
    28	that runs on every `cargo test`, exercises the identical production read SQL,
    29	and surfaces a perf + recall + structural signal in ~16 s.
    30	
    31	It does **not** replace the canonical verdict. Small-N latency is noisy and the
    32	synthetic embedder cannot meet the real-data recall/stress bounds, so the
    33	devloop tier deliberately does **not** assert the canonical budgets.
    34	
    35	---
    36	
    37	## Gate disposition: notify vs block (HITL-locked 2026-06-01)
    38	
    39	The governing rule for the devloop tier is **perf signals NOTIFY, structural
    40	invariants BLOCK**:
    41	
    42	| Signal | Disposition | Catches | Why this disposition |
    43	|---|---|---|---|
    44	| `assert_vec0_row_count_matches_ingest` | **hard assert (BLOCK)** | batch-collapse (`4a95cfd`) | deterministic correctness — a collapsed batch leaves `vector_default` short of the doc count; no flap risk |
    45	| `assert_fts_index_populated` | **hard assert (BLOCK)** | FTS path not wired | deterministic correctness |
    46	| latency p50 ≤ 50 ms / p99 ≤ 150 ms | **notify-only WARN** | gradual latency drift | small-N sample noise should not fail `cargo test`; PR-7 turns the trend into a CI gate |
    47	| **catastrophic ceiling** p50 > 500 ms / p99 > 1500 ms (10× soft) | **hard assert (BLOCK)** | scanner-throughput (`53a270d`) | an orders-of-magnitude inflation is unambiguously a regression, not noise |
    48	| recall@10 ≥ 0.85 (real embedder) | **notify-only WARN** | quantization-fidelity drift | noisy at small N; PR-7 owns the trend gate |
    49	| recall@10 (synthetic embedder) | **report-only** | — | synthetic vectors quantize poorly (~0.35 @ N≈1000) — a property of the DATA, not a regression (mirrors AC-019) |
    50	
    51	### Why a single hard catastrophic ceiling
    52	
    53	Notify-only latency alone would mean the scanner-throughput regression
    54	(`53a270d`, whose symptom is orders-of-magnitude p50/p99 inflation) no longer
    55	fails `cargo test`. The catastrophic ceiling at 10× the soft budget restores a
    56	hard RED for that regression while leaving routine noise to the notify path: a
    57	regression that inflates p50 from ~14 ms to hundreds of ms clears 500 ms; normal
    58	run-to-run wobble never does.
    59	
    60	### RED-shows evidence
    61	
    62	Both named regressions were re-introduced (symptom-injected at the gate seam) in
    63	a throwaway run and confirmed to RED-fail — see
    64	`dev/plans/runs/0.7.2-PR-6-output.json` (`red_shows_experiment`):
    65	
    66	- batch-collapse → `assert_vec0_row_count_matches_ingest` panics
    67	  (*"vector_default has 1 rows but 1000 … docs were ingested"*).
    68	- scanner-throughput → `enforce_catastrophic_ceiling` panics
    69	  (*"DEVLOOP CATASTROPHIC (013): p50=616ms > 500ms"*).
    70	
    71	---
    72	
    73	## Embedder: synthetic default, real opt-in
    74	
    75	- **Synthetic (`VaryingEmbedder`) — always-runs default.** Its embed is instant,
    76	  so the measured latency isolates *retrieval* (same rationale as canonical
    77	  AC-013). This is the inner-loop signal and the only path bound by the ≤30 s
    78	  budget. Its recall is report-only (see above).
    79	- **Real BGE — opt-in.** Enabled by `DEVLOOP_REAL_EMBEDDER=1` **and** the
    80	  `default-embedder` feature **and** a warm embed cache. Without the feature the
    81	  fixture SKIPs gracefully. The held-out query embeds are *live* candle inference
    82	  (queries are new text, not covered by the doc-body cache from PR-5), so the
    83	  real path is **not** bound by the ≤30 s budget — it is an occasional
    84	  end-to-end correctness exercise. On the real path the 0.85 recall floor WARN
    85	  is active.
    86	
    87	The PR-5 embedding cache (`data/corpus-data/.cache/embeddings/`) caches embed
    88	*inputs*, not query *results*: warm runs skip re-embedding doc bodies but the
    89	production bit-KNN + f32 rerank read path runs in full every time. The devloop
    90	tests therefore measure the real read path, never a cached short-circuit.
    91	
    92	---
    93	
    94	## Knob inventory (`DEVLOOP_*`)
    95	
    96	The devloop tier keeps its own knob surface, disjoint from the canonical
    97	`AC013_*` / `AC019_*` knobs, so neither contract bleeds into the other.
    98	
    99	| Knob | Effect | Default |
   100	|---|---|---|
   101	| `DEVLOOP_REAL_EMBEDDER=1` | use real BGE (requires `default-embedder` + warm cache) | unset → synthetic |
   102	| `FATHOMDB_CORPUS_CACHE_DIR` | override the PR-5 embed-cache dir (shared with the harness) | `data/corpus-data/.cache/embeddings/` |
   103	
   104	In-code budget constants (not env): `DEVLOOP_BUDGET_P50` (50 ms),
   105	`DEVLOOP_BUDGET_P99` (150 ms), `DEVLOOP_RECALL_FLOOR` (0.85),
   106	`DEVLOOP_CATASTROPHIC_MULT` (10×), `DEVLOOP_SAMPLES` (100), `DEVLOOP_SEED`.
   107	
   108	Devloop tests are **not** gated behind `AGENT_LONG` — that flag is the canonical
   109	tier's switch and the devloop tier must run unconditionally.
   110	
   111	---
   112	
   113	## The `DEVLOOP_NUMBERS` line (PR-7 consumes this)
   114	
   115	Each test emits one stable, parseable trend line on stderr:
   116	
   117	```
   118	DEVLOOP_NUMBERS ac=013 n=1000 samples=100 p50_ms=14 p99_ms=18 recall_at_10=NA cache=na embedder=synthetic
   119	DEVLOOP_NUMBERS ac=013b n=1000 samples=100 p50_ms=0 p99_ms=0 recall_at_10=0.3470 cache=na embedder=synthetic
   120	DEVLOOP_NUMBERS ac=019 n=1000 threads=4 per_thread=50 stress_ms=5728 baseline_p99_ms=16 stress_p99_ms=154 cache=na embedder=synthetic disposition=report_only
   121	```
   122	
   123	Breach notifications (notify-only, do not fail):
   124	
   125	```
   126	DEVLOOP_PERF_WARN ac=013 metric=p50 value_ms=60 budget_ms=50 status=OVER
   127	DEVLOOP_PERF_WARN ac=013b metric=recall_at_10 value=0.83 floor=0.85 status=UNDER   # real embedder only
   128	DEVLOOP_PERF_INFO ac=013b metric=recall_at_10 disposition=report_only embedder=synthetic
   129	```
   130	
   131	The `ac=`, `p50_ms=`, `p99_ms=`, `recall_at_10=` fields are the stable contract
   132	**PR-7** (perf-regression detection, `dev/perf-history/`) parses to build the
   133	per-(ac, embedder) trend and apply its 10 %-latency / 0.02-recall thresholds.
   134	Adding fields is safe; renaming or reordering the keyed fields is a breaking
   135	change to that contract.
   136	
   137	---
   138	
   139	## See also
   140	
   141	- `dev/adr/ADR-0.7.0-text-query-latency-gates-revised.md` — the tiered canonical
   142	  budget (10k binding; 100k/1M post-1.0 ANN work).
   143	- `crates/fathomdb-engine/tests/support/corpus_harness.rs` — PR-5 `CorpusFixture`
   144	  + embed cache the devloop tier consumes.
   145	- `dev/perf-history/` + the perf-regression check (PR-7) — turns the
   146	  `DEVLOOP_NUMBERS` trend into a regression gate.

